Ma'am, open up.
Just open up, please!

256
00:12:33,880 --> 00:12:34,790
- Ma'am?
- It's important.

257
00:12:34,840 --> 00:12:35,875
What?

258
00:12:35,920 --> 00:12:37,433
Oh, gosh!

259
00:12:37,480 --> 00:12:38,708
We don't open
for half an hour!

260
00:12:38,760 --> 00:12:40,512
Open the door, please.
Just open the door.

261
00:12:40,560 --> 00:12:41,470
It's important.

262
00:12:41,520 --> 00:12:43,351
l-I'm sorry, we don't open
for half an hour.

263
00:12:43,400 --> 00:12:44,435
What's your name, ma'am?

264
00:12:44,480 --> 00:12:45,549
Darcy.

265
00:12:45,600 --> 00:12:46,635
Darcy. That's a pretty name.

266
00:12:46,680 --> 00:12:48,318
I'm in a bit of a fix.
I need a suit for my kid.

267
00:12:48,360 --> 00:12:49,270
This is my son Frank.

268
00:12:49,320 --> 00:12:50,230
Oh, hi.

269
00:12:50,280 --> 00:12:51,190
He needs a black suit.

270
00:12:51,240 --> 00:12:52,559
Black suit...

271
00:12:52,600 --> 00:12:53,874
There was a death in the family.

272
00:12:53,920 --> 00:12:55,319
My father, 85 years old,
war hero.

273
00:12:55,360 --> 00:12:57,237
Yeah?

274
00:12:57,280 --> 00:12:59,919
There's a funeral
this afternoon, military funeral

275
00:12:59,960 --> 00:13:01,996
planes flying overhead,
21-gun salute.

276
00:13:02,040 --> 00:13:03,268
Geez.

277
00:13:03,320 --> 00:13:06,198
Frank needs to borrow a suit
for a couple of hours.

278
00:13:06,240 --> 00:13:09,118
I'm sorry, we don't loan suits,
and we're not open.

279
00:13:09,160 --> 00:13:10,434
Darcy... Darcy, please.

280
00:13:10,480 --> 00:13:12,277
<i>-(sighs)</i>
- Come back.

281
00:13:12,320 --> 00:13:14,311
Darcy... is this yours?

282
00:13:14,360 --> 00:13:16,078
<i>(jingles)</i>

283
00:13:19,800 --> 00:13:22,394
I just found it
in the parking lot.

284
00:13:22,440 --> 00:13:24,476
Uh-huh.

285
00:13:24,520 --> 00:13:26,750
It must've slipped
right off your neck.

286
00:13:28,560 --> 00:13:29,470
<i>(tires screeching)</i>

287
00:13:29,520 --> 00:13:31,431
Don't hit the curb.

288
00:13:33,680 --> 00:13:35,238
<i>(brakes squeaking)</i>

289
00:13:36,240 --> 00:13:37,992
Now get out,
walk around the back

290
00:13:38,040 --> 00:13:39,712
and hold the door open for me.

291
00:13:42,400 --> 00:13:44,311
<i>(car horn honks)</i>

292
00:13:48,840 --> 00:13:49,989
All right.

293
00:13:50,040 --> 00:13:51,189
What's next?

294
00:13:51,240 --> 00:13:52,559
Okay, stop grinning.

295
00:13:52,600 --> 00:13:55,831
When I get inside, you go back
to the front seat and wait.

296
00:13:55,880 --> 00:13:58,269
Even if a cop comes
and writes you a ticket

297
00:13:58,320 --> 00:14:00,276
you don't move the car,
understood?

298
00:14:00,320 --> 00:14:02,117
Dad, wha-what's all this for?

299
00:14:02,160 --> 00:14:04,116
You know why the Yankees
always win, Frank?

300
00:14:04,160 --> 00:14:05,718
'Cause they have Mickey Mantle?

301
00:14:05,760 --> 00:14:07,352
No, it's 'cause the other teams

302
00:14:07,400 --> 00:14:09,709
can't stop staring
at those damn pinstripes.

303
00:14:09,760 --> 00:14:10,715
Watch this.

304
00:14:10,760 --> 00:14:12,557
The manager
of Chase Manhattan Bank

305
00:14:12,600 --> 00:14:16,798
is about to open the door
for your father.

306
00:14:18,400 --> 00:14:20,675
Mr. Abagnale, um

307
00:14:20,720 --> 00:14:22,711
we don't usually
loan money to people

308
00:14:22,760 --> 00:14:25,035
who have unresolved business
with the IRS.

309
00:14:25,080 --> 00:14:26,798
That's a misunderstanding.

310
00:14:26,840 --> 00:14:28,432
I hired the wrong guy
to do my books.

311
00:14:28,480 --> 00:14:30,118
A mistake, I...
anybody could make it.

312
00:14:30,160 --> 00:14:32,355
I just need you guys
to help me weather the storm.

313
00:14:32,400 --> 00:14:36,678
Sir, you're being investigated
by the government for tax fraud.

314
00:14:36,720 --> 00:14:38,711
My store is a landmark
in New Rochelle.

315
00:14:38,760 --> 00:14:40,591
I have customers
all over New York.

316
00:14:40,640 --> 00:14:43,108
Well, you're not a customer
at Chase Manhattan.

317
00:14:43,160 --> 00:14:44,149
We don't know you.

318
00:14:44,200 --> 00:14:45,872
I'm sure your bank
in New Rochelle

319
00:14:45,920 --> 00:14:47,876
they know you,
they could help you out.

320
00:14:47,920 --> 00:14:49,399
My bank went out of business.

321
00:14:49,440 --> 00:14:51,749
Banks like this one put
them out of business.

322
00:14:51,800 --> 00:14:53,836
Now, I know I made a mistake,
I admit that

323
00:14:53,880 --> 00:14:55,233
but these people want blood.

324
00:14:55,280 --> 00:14:56,190
They want my store.

325
00:14:56,240 --> 00:14:58,037
They've threatened
to put me in jail.

326
00:14:58,080 --> 00:14:59,638
<i>(stammers)</i>

327
00:14:59,680 --> 00:15:01,113
This is America, right?

328
00:15:01,160 --> 00:15:02,149
I'm not a criminal.

329
00:15:02,200 --> 00:15:03,633
I'm a Medal of Honor winner

330
00:15:03,680 --> 00:15:06,319
a lifetime member
of the New Rochelle Rotary Club.

331
00:15:06,360 --> 00:15:09,193
All I'm asking is for you
to help me beat these guys.

332
00:15:09,240 --> 00:15:11,629
It's not a question
of winning and losing.

333
00:15:11,680 --> 00:15:13,113
It's a question of risk.

334
00:15:13,160 --> 00:15:15,720
You're the largest bank
in the world.

335
00:15:15,760 --> 00:15:17,239
Where's the fu...

336
00:15:17,280 --> 00:15:19,919
Whe... Where's the risk?

337
00:15:24,840 --> 00:15:27,673
Dad, how could you just let him
take our car like that?

338
00:15:27,720 --> 00:15:29,631
He didn't take anything.
We took him.

339
00:15:29,680 --> 00:15:30,749
He overpaid by $500.

340
00:15:30,800 --> 00:15:33,917
Come on, Frank.

341
00:15:33,960 --> 00:15:35,313
Let's return the suit.

342
00:15:35,360 --> 00:15:37,271
<i>(Paula sobbing)</i>

343
00:15:42,880 --> 00:15:44,279
This place is good.

344
00:15:44,320 --> 00:15:46,151
It's small but, you know

345
00:15:46,200 --> 00:15:48,634
it's going to be
a lot less work.

346
00:15:48,680 --> 00:15:50,159
A lot less work for you.

347
00:15:50,200 --> 00:15:52,839
<i>(jackhammer drilling</i>
<i>in distance)</i>

348
00:16:00,920 --> 00:16:02,592
<i>(keys clank)</i>

349
00:16:12,400 --> 00:16:13,628
FRANK:
Hey, Dad.

350
00:16:13,680 --> 00:16:15,591
Hi.

351
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:20,956
Where's your mother?

352
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:22,069
I don't know.

353
00:16:22,120 --> 00:16:26,352
She said something
about going to look for a job.

354
00:16:27,640 --> 00:16:28,709
What's she gonna be

355
00:16:28,760 --> 00:16:30,591
a shoe salesman
at a centipede farm?

356
00:16:30,640 --> 00:16:31,755
<i>(laughing)</i>

357
00:16:31,800 --> 00:16:34,598
<i>(both laughing)</i>

358
00:16:36,480 --> 00:16:37,879
What are you doing?

359
00:16:37,920 --> 00:16:39,399
<i>(both laughing)</i>

360
00:16:39,440 --> 00:16:41,590
You want some pancakes?

361
00:16:41,640 --> 00:16:42,550
For dinner?

362
00:16:42,600 --> 00:16:44,397
On my son's 16th birthday?

363
00:16:44,440 --> 00:16:46,431
We're not gonna eat pancakes.

364
00:16:48,920 --> 00:16:51,388
Come on, why are you looking
at me like that?

365
00:16:51,440 --> 00:16:52,634
You thought I forgot?

366
00:16:52,680 --> 00:16:55,558
- I didn't think you forgot.
- I opened a checking account

367
00:16:55,600 --> 00:16:57,272
in your name.

368
00:16:57,320 --> 00:16:58,639
I put $25 in the account

369
00:16:58,680 --> 00:17:00,398
so you can buy
whatever you want.

370
00:17:00,440 --> 00:17:01,668
Don't tell your mother.

371
00:17:01,720 --> 00:17:02,709
I won't.

372
00:17:02,760 --> 00:17:03,795
Thanks, Dad.

373
00:17:03,840 --> 00:17:04,829
Yep.

374
00:17:04,880 --> 00:17:07,792
Didn't that bank turn you down
for a loan, though?

375
00:17:07,840 --> 00:17:09,432
Yes, they all turned me down.

376
00:17:09,480 --> 00:17:10,754
<i>(chuckles)</i>

377
00:17:10,800 --> 00:17:12,950
Then why you opening
a banking account with them?

378
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:15,150
Well, because one day,
you'll want something

379
00:17:15,200 --> 00:17:16,997
from these people...
a house, a car.

380
00:17:17,040 --> 00:17:19,918
They have all the money.

381
00:17:22,560 --> 00:17:25,313
There's 50 checks there, Frank

382
00:17:25,360 --> 00:17:29,717
which means, from this day on...

383
00:17:29,760 --> 00:17:31,830
you're in their little club.

384
00:17:31,880 --> 00:17:35,190
I'm in their little club.

385
00:17:35,240 --> 00:17:37,231
You got that, you got it all.

386
00:17:37,280 --> 00:17:41,432
It's even got my name there,
huh?

387
00:17:41,480 --> 00:17:42,754
To the moon.

388
00:17:42,800 --> 00:17:47,555
- To the moon!
- To the moon.

389
00:17:47,800 --> 00:17:49,518
<i>(bells tolling)</i>

390
00:17:55,560 --> 00:17:58,313
See that? It's just a school.

391
00:17:58,360 --> 00:17:59,998
No different than Westbourne.

392
00:18:00,040 --> 00:18:03,669
Ma... you said you were
going to quit.

393
00:18:06,720 --> 00:18:10,030
Frankie, you don't have
to wear the uniform here.

394
00:18:10,080 --> 00:18:12,913
Why don't you take off
your jacket?

395
00:18:12,960 --> 00:18:15,793
I'm used to it.

396
00:18:15,840 --> 00:18:17,751
<i>(indistinct conversation)</i>

397
00:18:20,080 --> 00:18:21,115
Excuse me.

398
00:18:21,160 --> 00:18:22,070
Oh, yes?

399
00:18:22,120 --> 00:18:23,917
Do you know
where room 17 French is?

400
00:18:23,960 --> 00:18:25,598
GIRL:
Yeah, it's...

401
00:18:25,640 --> 00:18:27,358
<i>(snickering)</i>

402
00:18:31,160 --> 00:18:33,515
<i>(school bell ringing)</i>

403
00:18:33,560 --> 00:18:35,357
BO Y:
But you frickin' killed him.

404
00:18:35,400 --> 00:18:38,710
<i>(loud indistinct conversation)</i>

405
00:18:38,760 --> 00:18:40,751
You selling encyclopedias?

406
00:18:40,800 --> 00:18:44,156
Yeah, he looks like
a substitute teacher.

407
00:18:51,640 --> 00:18:54,074
<i>(boy laughing)</i>

408
00:18:54,120 --> 00:18:58,318
<i>(loud conversation</i>
<i>and laughter continues)</i>

409
00:18:58,360 --> 00:19:00,396
Quiet down, people!

410
00:19:00,440 --> 00:19:02,635
My name is Mr. Abagnale!

411
00:19:02,680 --> 00:19:05,717
That's Abagnale, not Abagnahlee

412
00:19:05,760 --> 00:19:09,036
not Abagnaylee, but Abagnale!

413
00:19:09,080 --> 00:19:11,150
Now, somebody please tell me
where you left off

414
00:19:11,200 --> 00:19:13,111
in your textbooks.

415
00:19:14,520 --> 00:19:16,158
Excuse me, people,
if I need to ask again

416
00:19:16,200 --> 00:19:17,758
I'm going to write up
the entire class.

417
00:19:17,800 --> 00:19:20,030
Take your seats!

418
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:25,513
Chapter seven.

419
00:19:25,560 --> 00:19:27,835
Will you please open your
textbooks to, uh, chapter eight

420
00:19:27,880 --> 00:19:30,394
and we'll get started?

421
00:19:30,440 --> 00:19:31,839
Excuse me,
what's your name?

422
00:19:31,880 --> 00:19:32,949
Brad.

423
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:36,117
Brad, why don't you get up here
in front of the class here

424
00:19:36,160 --> 00:19:39,197
and read conversation
number five?

425
00:19:41,840 --> 00:19:44,479
<i>(pronouncing poorly)</i>:
<i>"Les Francais sonts</i>

426
00:19:44,520 --> 00:19:46,397
<i>"uh, generalement</i>

427
00:19:46,440 --> 00:19:49,113
<i>-"dans leur pais que... </i>
<i>-(students laughing)</i>

428
00:19:49,160 --> 00:19:51,879
<i>presque tout le monde</i>
<i>a cette impression..."</i>

429
00:19:51,920 --> 00:19:53,239
They sent for me.

430
00:19:53,280 --> 00:19:56,352
They said they needed a sub
for Roberta.

431
00:19:56,400 --> 00:19:59,073
I came all the way
from-from Dixon.

432
00:19:59,120 --> 00:20:01,190
Well, uh,
I always sub for Roberta.

433
00:20:01,240 --> 00:20:03,196
Excuse me,
why aren't you reading?

434
00:20:03,240 --> 00:20:04,389
<i>(continues reading)</i>

435
00:20:04,440 --> 00:20:07,034
I'll never come back to-to
Bellarmine Jefferson again!

436
00:20:07,080 --> 00:20:09,514
- You tell them not to call me!
<i>-(students laughing)</i>

437
00:20:09,560 --> 00:20:11,835
What do they think,
it's easy for a woman my age

438
00:20:11,880 --> 00:20:13,871
and all the money that it costs
to travel?

439
00:20:13,920 --> 00:20:15,638
I tell you,
they don't give a damn.

440
00:20:15,680 --> 00:20:16,954
<i>(students laughing)</i>

441
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:18,353
Mr. And Mrs. Abagnale

442
00:20:18,400 --> 00:20:21,517
this is not a question
of your son's attendance.

443
00:20:21,560 --> 00:20:24,552
I regret to inform you that,
for the past week

444
00:20:24,600 --> 00:20:28,070
Frank has been teaching
Mrs. Glasser's French class.

445
00:20:29,360 --> 00:20:30,588
He what?

446
00:20:30,640 --> 00:20:34,553
Your son has been pretending
to be a substitute teacher

447
00:20:34,600 --> 00:20:38,718
lecturing the students,
uh, giving out homework.

448
00:20:38,760 --> 00:20:42,150
Mrs. Glasser has been ill
and there was

449
00:20:42,200 --> 00:20:45,033
some confusion
with the real sub.

450
00:20:45,080 --> 00:20:48,390
Your son held a teacher-parent
conference yesterday

451
00:20:48,440 --> 00:20:50,749
and was planning
a class field trip

452
00:20:50,800 --> 00:20:53,189
to a French bread factory
in Trenton.

453
00:20:53,240 --> 00:20:56,676
Do you see the problem we have?

454
00:20:56,720 --> 00:20:58,597
- Mrs. Davenport?
- Yeah.

455
00:20:58,640 --> 00:21:00,995
Uh, I have a note to miss fifth
and sixth period today.

456
00:21:01,040 --> 00:21:01,950
Doctor's appointment.

457
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:03,991
- One moment.
<i>-(phone ringing)</i>

458
00:21:04,040 --> 00:21:05,268
I'll be right with you.

459
00:21:05,320 --> 00:21:06,230
<i>(whispering)</i>:
Hey...

460
00:21:06,280 --> 00:21:07,190
MRS. DAVENPORT:
Yes?

461
00:21:07,240 --> 00:21:08,389
You should fold it.

462
00:21:08,440 --> 00:21:09,429
What?

463
00:21:09,480 --> 00:21:11,038
That note. It's a fake, right?

464
00:21:11,080 --> 00:21:12,308
You should fold it.

465
00:21:12,360 --> 00:21:14,032
It's... It's a note from my mom.

466
00:21:14,080 --> 00:21:15,718
I have a doctor's appointment.

467
00:21:15,760 --> 00:21:18,479
Yeah, but there's no crease
in the paper.

468
00:21:18,520 --> 00:21:20,476
When your mom hands you a note
to miss school

469
00:21:20,520 --> 00:21:22,112
the first thing you do is,
you fold it

470
00:21:22,160 --> 00:21:23,513
and you put it in your pocket.

471
00:21:23,560 --> 00:21:26,597
I mean, if it's real,
where's the crease?

472
00:21:31,120 --> 00:21:33,031
<i>-(school bell ringing)</i>
<i>-(door opens)</i>

473
00:21:35,960 --> 00:21:37,234
<i>(quietly)</i>:
Frankie.

474
00:21:47,640 --> 00:21:50,712
<i>(both chuckling quietly)</i>

475
00:21:52,160 --> 00:21:54,037
Ma, I'm home.

476
00:21:54,080 --> 00:21:56,036
<i>(romantic music</i>
<i>plays on record player)</i>

477
00:21:56,080 --> 00:21:57,957
Oh, you remember
that girl Joanna

478
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:00,070
I was telling you about?

479
00:22:00,120 --> 00:22:03,078
I asked her out today.

480
00:22:03,120 --> 00:22:05,315
Think we're going to go
to the Junior Prom.

481
00:22:05,360 --> 00:22:07,237
<i>(record scratches, </i>
<i>music stops)</i>

482
00:22:07,280 --> 00:22:09,032
Ma, is this
my driver's license?

483
00:22:09,080 --> 00:22:10,798
That's all there is,
two bedrooms.

484
00:22:10,840 --> 00:22:13,070
Oh, Frankie.

485
00:22:13,120 --> 00:22:14,951
You remember Dad's friend?

486
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:16,797
Jack Barnes?

487
00:22:16,840 --> 00:22:18,068
From the club.

488
00:22:18,120 --> 00:22:19,075
Hello.

489
00:22:19,120 --> 00:22:20,951
He came by looking
for your father.

490
00:22:21,000 --> 00:22:23,594
I was giving him
a tour of the apartment.

491
00:22:23,640 --> 00:22:26,552
It's very, uh, uh,
spacious, Paula.

492
00:22:31,880 --> 00:22:34,030
Dad's at the store.

493
00:22:34,080 --> 00:22:36,913
So, Frank...
you're getting to look

494
00:22:36,960 --> 00:22:39,713
more like your old man
every day.

495
00:22:42,280 --> 00:22:44,555
Thanks for the sandwich, Paula.

496
00:22:44,600 --> 00:22:46,318
I'll see you later, eh?

497
00:22:46,360 --> 00:22:48,271
Wait.

498
00:22:52,200 --> 00:22:54,236
Is this yours?

499
00:22:54,280 --> 00:22:56,919
Oh.

500
00:22:56,960 --> 00:22:58,518
Well, thanks, Frank.

501
00:22:58,560 --> 00:23:00,790
Uh, that's the President's pin.

502
00:23:00,840 --> 00:23:03,149
I'd be in deep trouble
if I lost that.

503
00:23:05,080 --> 00:23:06,991
<i>(nervous chuckle)</i>

504
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:10,991
I'll see you all later, eh?

505
00:23:20,160 --> 00:23:22,196
Are you hungry, Frankie?

506
00:23:22,240 --> 00:23:24,549
I'll make you a sandwich.

507
00:23:32,360 --> 00:23:35,352
Jack wanted to talk business
with your father.

508
00:23:35,400 --> 00:23:39,188
He thinks we should get a lawyer
and sue the government.

509
00:23:40,680 --> 00:23:43,478
That is not legal,
what they're doing to us.

510
00:23:46,520 --> 00:23:48,431
Why aren't you saying anything?

511
00:23:54,560 --> 00:23:58,997
You're not going to tell him...
are you?

512
00:23:59,040 --> 00:24:00,678
<i>(quietly)</i>:
No.

513
00:24:00,720 --> 00:24:01,948
That's right.

514
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:04,560
There's nothing to tell.

515
00:24:04,600 --> 00:24:06,192
I'm going out for a few hours

516
00:24:06,240 --> 00:24:09,198
to visit some old friends
from the tennis club and...

517
00:24:09,240 --> 00:24:12,710
when I get home,
we'll all have dinner together.

518
00:24:12,760 --> 00:24:14,637
Right?

519
00:24:14,680 --> 00:24:16,591
But you won't say anything

520
00:24:16,640 --> 00:24:19,871
because it's...
it's just silly, isn't it?

521
00:24:19,920 --> 00:24:21,831
How could we sue anybody?

522
00:24:25,640 --> 00:24:29,918
Oh... do you need
some money, Frankie?

523
00:24:29,960 --> 00:24:33,589
A few dollars to buy
some record albums?

524
00:24:33,640 --> 00:24:36,632
Here, take five dollars.

525
00:24:36,680 --> 00:24:38,591
Or-Or ten.

526
00:24:43,880 --> 00:24:45,757
You promised you were going
to quit.

527
00:24:45,800 --> 00:24:47,711
<i>(slams)</i>

528
00:24:51,120 --> 00:24:53,588
<i>(children laughing)</i>

529
00:24:53,640 --> 00:24:56,029
<i>(dog barking in distance)</i>

530
00:25:04,520 --> 00:25:06,431
Ma, I'm home!

531
00:25:16,040 --> 00:25:17,951
<i>(door opens)</i>

532
00:25:20,720 --> 00:25:22,153
Hey, hey!

533
00:25:22,200 --> 00:25:23,474
You... You stay away from me,
hear me?

534
00:25:23,520 --> 00:25:25,158
You stay away from me...
I don't know who you are

535
00:25:25,200 --> 00:25:26,394
but if you ever
come back here again...

536
00:25:26,440 --> 00:25:28,590
Frankie! Frank, Frank,
calm down, will you?

537
00:25:28,640 --> 00:25:29,755
I'm Dick Kesner.

538
00:25:29,800 --> 00:25:31,870
Now, I want you
to leave your things here

539
00:25:31,920 --> 00:25:33,876
and follow me
into the next room, okay?

540
00:25:33,920 --> 00:25:35,399
They're all waiting for you.

541
00:25:38,360 --> 00:25:40,476
PAULA:
You don't have to be scared.

542
00:25:40,520 --> 00:25:42,397
I'm right here, Frank.
I'll always be here.

543
00:25:42,440 --> 00:25:44,078
But there are laws.

544
00:25:44,120 --> 00:25:46,236
Everything in this country has
to be legal.

545
00:25:46,280 --> 00:25:49,113
So what we need to do is
make some decisions.

546
00:25:49,160 --> 00:25:50,718
That's what Mr. Kesner
is here for.

547
00:25:50,760 --> 00:25:52,990
Many times these decisions
are left up to the courts

548
00:25:53,040 --> 00:25:54,439
but that can be
very expensive, Frank

549
00:25:54,480 --> 00:25:56,038
people fighting
over their children.

550
00:25:56,080 --> 00:25:57,638
Nobody is fighting.

551
00:25:57,680 --> 00:26:00,240
Look at me, Frank.
Nobody is fighting.

552
00:26:00,280 --> 00:26:02,475
<i>(speaking French)</i>

553
00:26:02,520 --> 00:26:04,715
<i>(quietly)</i>:
Dad, what's going on?

554
00:26:04,760 --> 00:26:06,193
Dad, what's going on?

555
00:26:06,240 --> 00:26:08,708
<i>(speaking French continues)</i>

556
00:26:08,760 --> 00:26:10,273
Do you remember your grandma,
Eve?

557
00:26:10,320 --> 00:26:11,958
She arrived this morning.

558
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:13,353
<i>(speaks French)</i>

559
00:26:13,400 --> 00:26:14,833
Hello.

560
00:26:22,840 --> 00:26:25,912
Do you understand what
we're saying to you, Frank?

561
00:26:27,480 --> 00:26:31,268
Your father and I
are getting a divorce.

562
00:26:31,320 --> 00:26:33,709
<i>(speaking French)</i>

563
00:26:33,760 --> 00:26:34,875
Nothing's gonna change.

564
00:26:34,920 --> 00:26:36,558
We're still gonna see
each other.

565
00:26:36,600 --> 00:26:38,431
Stop it, please, Frank.
Don't interrupt.

566
00:26:38,480 --> 00:26:40,675
Frank, you don't
have to read all of this.

567
00:26:40,720 --> 00:26:43,712
Most of it's for your parents...
boring adult business...

568
00:26:43,760 --> 00:26:46,399
but this paragraph right here,
this is important

569
00:26:46,440 --> 00:26:49,000
because it states
who you're gonna live with...

570
00:26:49,040 --> 00:26:50,917
after the divorce...

571
00:26:50,960 --> 00:26:52,791
whose custody you will be in.

572
00:26:52,840 --> 00:26:55,832
And there's a blank space
right here.

573
00:26:55,880 --> 00:26:56,790
<i>(Eve speaking French)</i>

574
00:26:56,840 --> 00:26:58,193
And I want you to go
into the kitchen

575
00:26:58,240 --> 00:26:59,753
sit at the table

576
00:26:59,800 --> 00:27:01,358
and put a name down.

577
00:27:01,400 --> 00:27:02,674
You can take
as long as you want

578
00:27:02,720 --> 00:27:04,278
but when you come back
into this room...

579
00:27:04,320 --> 00:27:06,788
<i>I want to see a name</i>
<i>on that line. </i>

580
00:27:06,840 --> 00:27:10,389
Frank, just write down a name
and this will all be over.

581
00:27:10,440 --> 00:27:12,271
It's gonna be okay.

582
00:27:12,320 --> 00:27:13,992
FRANK:
<i>Dad, what name? </i>

583
00:27:14,040 --> 00:27:15,109
Your mother or your father.

584
00:27:15,160 --> 00:27:17,196
Just put the name there.
It's as simple as that.

585
00:27:17,240 --> 00:27:20,118
And don't look so scared.

586
00:27:20,160 --> 00:27:21,832
It's not a test.

587
00:27:21,880 --> 00:27:23,791
<i>There's no wrong answer. </i>

588
00:27:26,120 --> 00:27:28,998
<i>(man announcing trains</i>
<i>indistinctly)</i>

589
00:27:31,880 --> 00:27:36,078
<i>(melancholy jazz playing)</i>

590
00:27:36,120 --> 00:27:37,030
Hi.

591
00:27:37,080 --> 00:27:38,115
<i>(panting)</i>

592
00:27:38,160 --> 00:27:39,593
One ticket to Grand Central,
please.

593
00:27:39,640 --> 00:27:42,757
That'll be $3.50, sir.

594
00:27:42,800 --> 00:27:45,519
Is it okay
if I write you a check?

595
00:27:50,360 --> 00:27:53,033
Carl, when do I get
to call my father?

596
00:27:53,080 --> 00:27:55,514
You can call him
when we get to New York.

597
00:27:55,560 --> 00:27:57,312
We leave for the airport
in seven hours.

598
00:27:57,360 --> 00:27:58,679
Paris, France 1969

599
00:27:58,720 --> 00:28:00,870
Until then, just sit there.

600
00:28:00,920 --> 00:28:03,514
Be quiet.

601
00:28:03,560 --> 00:28:05,790
You know, Carl,
on the other side of the hotel

602
00:28:05,840 --> 00:28:07,592
they got suites
that face the park.

603
00:28:08,680 --> 00:28:11,672
It's the best room
the FBI can afford.

604
00:28:13,920 --> 00:28:15,911
It's okay, I've stayed in worse.

605
00:28:15,960 --> 00:28:17,234
<i>Mr. Mudrick... </i>

606
00:28:17,280 --> 00:28:18,508
Mr. Mudrick, please.
You have to listen.

607
00:28:18,560 --> 00:28:20,232
I don't want to hear your story.

608
00:28:20,280 --> 00:28:21,952
This is two checks that bounced.

609
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:23,672
You know how much trouble
I'm in?

610
00:28:23,720 --> 00:28:26,473
No, but listen, I'm telling you,
the bank, they made the mistake.

611
00:28:26,520 --> 00:28:27,953
I'll write you another check
right now!

612
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:29,831
What, do I look like
I was born yesterday?

613
00:28:29,880 --> 00:28:31,632
Look, it's midnight,
Mr. Mudrick.

614
00:28:31,680 --> 00:28:32,590
Where am I gonna go?

615
00:28:32,640 --> 00:28:34,153
You're a goddamn kid.

616
00:28:34,200 --> 00:28:36,111
Go home.

617
00:28:37,760 --> 00:28:39,990
<i>(baby crying in distance)</i>

618
00:28:57,480 --> 00:29:01,837
<i>~ ~</i>

619
00:29:10,560 --> 00:29:13,677
<i>~ ~</i>

620
00:29:21,800 --> 00:29:22,994
I mean, I hope you understand.

621
00:29:23,040 --> 00:29:24,758
My boss sent me to Brooklyn,
then Queens.

622
00:29:24,800 --> 00:29:26,153
Now he wants me in Long Island

623
00:29:26,200 --> 00:29:28,555
to take a few clients out
for a night on the town.

624
00:29:28,600 --> 00:29:31,990
I'm sorry, but we're not allowed
to cash checks from other banks.

625
00:29:32,040 --> 00:29:34,156
How would we know
if they were any good?

626
00:29:34,200 --> 00:29:35,838
What did you say your name was?

627
00:29:35,880 --> 00:29:36,949
Ashley.

628
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:39,992
Ashley... you know what I found
on the sidewalk out there?

629
00:29:45,240 --> 00:29:47,310
Must've slipped
right off your neck.

630
00:29:51,640 --> 00:29:55,110
Is there something
I can help you with, son?

631
00:29:55,160 --> 00:29:57,435
Well, you see, it's my
grandmother's birthday next week

632
00:29:57,480 --> 00:29:59,391
and I want to get her
something extra-special.

633
00:29:59,440 --> 00:30:01,032
<i>Please, I mean</i>

634
00:30:01,080 --> 00:30:03,389
it's my midterm next week
and my books were stolen.

635
00:30:03,440 --> 00:30:04,475
<i>(raspy coughing)</i>

636
00:30:04,520 --> 00:30:06,317
Please, it's just five dollars.

637
00:30:06,360 --> 00:30:07,918
No one would have to know.

638
00:30:07,960 --> 00:30:10,428
I'm sorry,
but we are not allowed

639
00:30:10,480 --> 00:30:13,677
to take checks
from people we don't know.

640
00:30:22,400 --> 00:30:24,311
<i>(horns honking, </i>
<i>whistle blowing)</i>

641
00:30:33,440 --> 00:30:36,512
<i>~ ~</i>

642
00:30:45,720 --> 00:30:47,676
<i>(women laughing)</i>

643
00:30:53,720 --> 00:30:55,472
Pleasure to have you back,
Captain Carlson.

644
00:30:55,520 --> 00:30:56,873
What do you think, Angelo?

645
00:30:56,920 --> 00:30:58,433
The tomatoes are ripe
this afternoon.

646
00:30:58,480 --> 00:31:00,391
<i>(women giggling)</i>

647
00:31:06,080 --> 00:31:07,149
Well, what have we here?

648
00:31:07,200 --> 00:31:09,111
- Can I have your autograph?
- You betcha.

649
00:31:09,160 --> 00:31:11,071
- Can I have your autograph, too?
- You gonna be a pilot?

650
00:31:11,120 --> 00:31:13,156
- Mm-hmm!
- All right, then.

651
00:31:13,200 --> 00:31:14,599
There you go.
Work hard in school.

652
00:31:14,640 --> 00:31:15,914
FRANK:
<i>Dear Dad: </i>

653
00:31:15,960 --> 00:31:18,394
<i>I have decided to become</i>
<i>an airline pilot. </i>

654
00:31:18,440 --> 00:31:20,715
<i>I have applied</i>
<i>to all the big airlines</i>

655
00:31:20,760 --> 00:31:23,672
<i>and I have several</i>
<i>promising interviews lined up. </i>

656
00:31:23,720 --> 00:31:25,358
<i>How's Mom? </i>

657
00:31:25,400 --> 00:31:27,277
<i>Have you called her lately? </i>

658
00:31:27,320 --> 00:31:29,311
<i>Love, your son, Frank. </i>

659
00:31:32,520 --> 00:31:34,272
Hello.

660
00:31:34,320 --> 00:31:36,515
I'm Frank Black
from Murrow High School

661
00:31:36,560 --> 00:31:39,028
and I have an appointment
with Mr. Morgan.

662
00:31:39,080 --> 00:31:40,274
You're the young man

663
00:31:40,320 --> 00:31:42,117
who's writing the article
for the school paper.

664
00:31:42,160 --> 00:31:43,593
Yes, ma'am, that's me.
I want to know

665
00:31:43,640 --> 00:31:45,517
everything there is to know
about being a pilot.

666
00:31:45,560 --> 00:31:47,073
What airports
does Pan Am fly to?

667
00:31:47,120 --> 00:31:48,758
What does a pilot make
in a year?

668
00:31:48,800 --> 00:31:51,030
And who tells them
where they're gonna fly to?

669
00:31:51,080 --> 00:31:52,195
Whoa, whoa, whoa. Slow down.

670
00:31:52,240 --> 00:31:53,355
Just take 'em one at a time.

671
00:31:53,400 --> 00:31:54,515
All right. What does it mean

672
00:31:54,560 --> 00:31:56,073
when one pilot says
to another pilot:

673
00:31:56,120 --> 00:31:57,519
"What kind of equipment
are you on?"

674
00:31:57,560 --> 00:31:59,949
They just want to know what kind
of aircraft you're flying:

675
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:01,319
Is it a DC-8, 707,
Constellation?

676
00:32:01,360 --> 00:32:03,920
And what about those I.D. badges
that I've seen pilots wear?

677
00:32:03,960 --> 00:32:06,030
Well, every pilot has to have
two things with him

678
00:32:06,080 --> 00:32:08,116
at all times: One is
his airline personnel badge...

679
00:32:08,160 --> 00:32:10,037
Iooks just like this one here,
from Pan Am...

680
00:32:10,080 --> 00:32:12,594
the other one is
their FAA license...

681
00:32:12,640 --> 00:32:14,870
and that looks just like this.

682
00:32:14,920 --> 00:32:18,469
Oh. Sir, do you think I can
make a copy of this

683
00:32:18,520 --> 00:32:20,238
to put into my article?

684
00:32:20,280 --> 00:32:21,998
Oh, Frank,
you can have that one.

685
00:32:22,040 --> 00:32:23,314
It's three years expired.

686
00:32:23,360 --> 00:32:24,873
Aw, thanks!
And what about your I.D. badge?

687
00:32:24,920 --> 00:32:26,319
You have an extra one
I could borrow?

688
00:32:26,360 --> 00:32:28,237
Oh, no, I can't help you there.

689
00:32:28,280 --> 00:32:30,111
Those are special-ordered
from Polaroid.

690
00:32:30,160 --> 00:32:31,593
The only way
to get one of those

691
00:32:31,640 --> 00:32:34,108
is to become a real live pilot
for Pan American Airways.

692
00:32:34,680 --> 00:32:36,830
<i>(dialing phone)</i>

693
00:32:36,880 --> 00:32:38,711
<i>(car horns honking, </i>
<i>whistle blowing)</i>

694
00:32:38,760 --> 00:32:40,273
WOMAN <i>(over phone)</i>:
Pan Am, may I help you?

695
00:32:40,320 --> 00:32:41,673
FRANK <i>(Southern accent)</i>:
Yeah, hello.

696
00:32:41,720 --> 00:32:42,675
I'm calling about a uniform.

697
00:32:42,720 --> 00:32:44,438
WOMAN:
Hold for Purchasing.

698
00:32:44,480 --> 00:32:45,390
FRANK:
Thank you.

699
00:32:45,440 --> 00:32:46,668
WOMAN 2:
Purchasing.

700
00:32:46,720 --> 00:32:48,597
FRANK <i>(Southern accent)</i>:
Hi. I'm a copilot

701
00:32:48,640 --> 00:32:49,834
based out of San Francisco.

702
00:32:49,880 --> 00:32:51,677
I flew a flight
into New York last night

703
00:32:51,720 --> 00:32:52,675
but the problem is

704
00:32:52,720 --> 00:32:54,199
I'm headed out to, uh, Paris
in three hours.

705
00:32:54,240 --> 00:32:55,992
WOMAN 2:
How can we help you?

706
00:32:56,040 --> 00:32:57,314
FRANK:
I sent my uniform

707
00:32:57,360 --> 00:32:59,112
to be cleaned through the hotel

708
00:32:59,160 --> 00:33:01,390
and I... I guess
they must have lost it.

709
00:33:01,440 --> 00:33:03,795
WOMAN 2:
<i>They lost a uniform. </i>
<i>Happens all the time. </i>

710
00:33:03,840 --> 00:33:05,751
<i>Go down to the Well-Built</i>
<i>Uniform Company</i>

711
00:33:05,800 --> 00:33:06,835
<i>at Ninth and Broadway. </i>

712
00:33:06,880 --> 00:33:08,233
<i>They're our uniform supplier. </i>

713
00:33:08,280 --> 00:33:09,872
<i>I'll tell Mr. Rosen</i>
<i>you're coming. </i>

714
00:33:09,920 --> 00:33:12,036
ROSEN:
You look too young
to be a pilot.

715
00:33:12,080 --> 00:33:13,718
I'm a copilot.

716
00:33:13,760 --> 00:33:15,318
Why so nervous?

717
00:33:15,360 --> 00:33:17,112
How would you feel if you, uh

718
00:33:17,160 --> 00:33:19,594
Iost your uniform
first week on the job?

719
00:33:19,640 --> 00:33:21,119
Relax.

720
00:33:21,160 --> 00:33:23,594
Pan Am's got lots of uniforms.

721
00:33:23,640 --> 00:33:25,790
It's gonna be $164.

722
00:33:25,840 --> 00:33:28,035
Great. I'Il, uh,
I'll write you a check.

723
00:33:28,080 --> 00:33:30,071
Sorry, no checks, no cash.

724
00:33:30,120 --> 00:33:32,156
You'll have to fill in
your employee I.D. number

725
00:33:32,200 --> 00:33:33,235
and then I'll bill Pan Am.

726
00:33:33,280 --> 00:33:35,157
They'll take it out
of your next paycheck.

727
00:33:37,240 --> 00:33:38,832
Even better.

728
00:33:40,760 --> 00:33:42,637
FRANK:
<i>Dear Dad: </i>

729
00:33:42,680 --> 00:33:45,433
<i>You always told me that an</i>
<i>honest man has nothing to fear. </i>

730
00:33:45,480 --> 00:33:47,391
<i>So I'm trying my best</i>
<i>not to be afraid. </i>

731
00:33:47,440 --> 00:33:51,718
<i>I'm sorry I ran away, </i>
<i>but you don't have to worry. </i>

732
00:33:51,760 --> 00:33:53,751
<i>I'm gonna get it all back</i>
<i>now, Daddy. </i>

733
00:33:53,800 --> 00:33:56,075
<i>I promise. </i>
<i>I'm going to get it all back. </i>

734
00:33:56,120 --> 00:33:58,031
<i>(approving murmur)</i>

735
00:34:01,600 --> 00:34:03,511
GIRL:
Are you a real live pilot?

736
00:34:03,560 --> 00:34:05,630
I sure am, little lady.
What's your name?

737
00:34:05,680 --> 00:34:06,590
Celine.

738
00:34:06,640 --> 00:34:08,437
Celine, it's a pleasure
to meet you.

739
00:34:08,480 --> 00:34:10,471
It's a pleasure
to meet you, too.

740
00:34:13,920 --> 00:34:16,593
That's fifty, seventy

741
00:34:16,640 --> 00:34:20,349
eighty, ninety,
one hundred dollars.

742
00:34:20,400 --> 00:34:22,197
You have yourself a great time
in Paris.

743
00:34:22,240 --> 00:34:23,753
I always do.

744
00:34:23,800 --> 00:34:26,633
Excuse me.

745
00:34:26,680 --> 00:34:28,238
I'm John Modiger.
I manage this branch.

746
00:34:28,280 --> 00:34:29,633
I want to thank you
for coming in

747
00:34:29,680 --> 00:34:30,749
and using our institution.

748
00:34:30,800 --> 00:34:32,438
Well, it's a pleasure
to meet you, John.

749
00:34:32,480 --> 00:34:33,390
I'll be back again.

750
00:34:33,440 --> 00:34:34,350
Good.

751
00:34:34,400 --> 00:34:36,152
Have you stayed with us before?

752
00:34:36,200 --> 00:34:39,431
Uh, no, I've been primarily
based on the West Coast.

753
00:34:39,480 --> 00:34:42,677
Is it all right if I write you
a check for the room?

754
00:34:42,720 --> 00:34:43,709
No problem, sir.

755
00:34:43,760 --> 00:34:45,671
Great.

756
00:34:52,720 --> 00:34:53,835
Uh...

757
00:34:53,880 --> 00:34:54,835
I was also wondering

758
00:34:54,880 --> 00:34:56,677
if I could write you
