<i>He must've got wise to us. </i>

2238
01:41:00,600 --> 01:41:02,079
HANRATTY:
<i>Maybe he was tipped. </i>

2239
01:41:02,120 --> 01:41:03,758
If he's not here today,
he'll be tomorrow.

2240
01:41:03,800 --> 01:41:05,518
We'll get him before
he leaves the country.

2241
01:41:05,560 --> 01:41:06,879
He doesn't have a passport.

2242
01:41:06,920 --> 01:41:09,229
For the last six months, he's
gone to Harvard and Berkeley.

2243
01:41:09,280 --> 01:41:10,633
I'm betting he can get
a passport.

2244
01:41:10,680 --> 01:41:12,398
So we have all our men
waiting for him here

2245
01:41:12,440 --> 01:41:13,350
in Miami International.

2246
01:41:13,400 --> 01:41:15,038
He's used it before.
He knows the layout.

2247
01:41:15,080 --> 01:41:16,877
I talked to Miami police;
they've offered us

2248
01:41:16,920 --> 01:41:18,512
50 uniformed cops
in two shifts of 25.

2249
01:41:18,560 --> 01:41:20,596
With our guys, that's almost
100 men in one airport.

2250
01:41:20,640 --> 01:41:22,358
Don't you think
we should spread it around?

2251
01:41:22,400 --> 01:41:23,958
No, no, this is the exit point.

2252
01:41:24,000 --> 01:41:26,116
Well, how do you know
he hasn't rented a car

2253
01:41:26,160 --> 01:41:28,276
and driven to airports
in New York, Atlanta?

2254
01:41:28,320 --> 01:41:29,753
Because I'm not in New York.

2255
01:41:29,800 --> 01:41:30,994
I'm not in Atlanta.

2256
01:41:31,040 --> 01:41:32,837
Yes, this is, uh, Frank Roberts

2257
01:41:32,880 --> 01:41:34,836
and I'm letting
all the universities

2258
01:41:34,880 --> 01:41:37,599
in the area know
that Pan Am will be initiating

2259
01:41:37,640 --> 01:41:39,596
a new recruiting program
this year.

2260
01:41:39,640 --> 01:41:42,757
I'Il, uh, be stopping
by your campus tomorrow morning.

2261
01:41:42,800 --> 01:41:45,712
Thank you all very much
for coming.

2262
01:41:45,760 --> 01:41:46,875
At the end of the day

2263
01:41:46,920 --> 01:41:49,912
I'll be choosing eight
young ladies to be a part of...

2264
01:41:49,960 --> 01:41:51,473
<i>(cheering and laughter)</i>

2265
01:41:51,520 --> 01:41:54,193
...Pan Am's future stewardess
flight crew program.

2266
01:41:54,240 --> 01:41:56,708
Now, these eight young ladies
will accompany me

2267
01:41:56,760 --> 01:41:59,672
on a two-month public relations
tour through Europe.

2268
01:41:59,720 --> 01:42:00,948
<i>(women squealing)</i>

2269
01:42:01,000 --> 01:42:03,560
They will discover firsthand
what it takes

2270
01:42:03,600 --> 01:42:05,591
to be a Pan American stewardess.

2271
01:42:05,640 --> 01:42:07,392
<i>(cheering)</i>

2272
01:42:07,440 --> 01:42:09,874
HANRATTY:
Give me at least two men...

2273
01:42:09,920 --> 01:42:12,388
Nah, one man
per every two counters.

2274
01:42:12,440 --> 01:42:13,714
- Mm-hmm.
- All right?

2275
01:42:13,760 --> 01:42:15,193
Amdursky?

2276
01:42:15,240 --> 01:42:17,117
Yeah?

2277
01:42:17,160 --> 01:42:19,196
Make sure your uniforms
are covering

2278
01:42:19,240 --> 01:42:21,117
the sidewalk entrances
and exits.

2279
01:42:21,160 --> 01:42:24,470
Hey... let's have, uh, periodic
sweeps of the men's lav.

2280
01:42:24,520 --> 01:42:26,829
You, here.

2281
01:42:26,880 --> 01:42:30,509
What qualifies me
to be a future stewardess?

2282
01:42:30,560 --> 01:42:32,994
Well, I think
that I'm really friendly

2283
01:42:33,040 --> 01:42:34,678
and I can really help out

2284
01:42:34,720 --> 01:42:38,235
and, um, make people
feel welcome on the plane and...

2285
01:42:38,280 --> 01:42:40,669
We'll be traveling
at 6,000 miles per hour

2286
01:42:40,720 --> 01:42:42,312
at an altitude of 300 feet.

2287
01:42:42,360 --> 01:42:47,309
<i>~</i> All my bags are packed,
I'm ready to go<i>... ~</i>

2288
01:42:47,360 --> 01:42:49,510
<i>(playing dramatic piano intro)</i>

2289
01:42:49,560 --> 01:42:50,879
Ilene Anderson.

2290
01:42:50,920 --> 01:42:53,070
<i>(squealing and applause)</i>

2291
01:42:53,120 --> 01:42:58,035
<i>(pianist playing</i>
<i>"Come Fly With Me")</i>

2292
01:42:58,080 --> 01:43:00,230
Miggy Acker.

2293
01:43:00,280 --> 01:43:02,669
<i>(excited squealing)</i>

2294
01:43:04,280 --> 01:43:06,748
Debra Jo McMillan.

2295
01:43:12,320 --> 01:43:14,470
Candy Heston.

2296
01:43:14,520 --> 01:43:21,995
FRANK SINATRA:
<i>~</i> Come fly with me,
let's fly, let's fly away <i>~</i>

2297
01:43:22,040 --> 01:43:25,032
<i>~</i> If you can use
some exotic booze <i>~</i>

2298
01:43:25,080 --> 01:43:28,436
<i>~</i> There's a bar in far Bombay <i>~</i>

2299
01:43:28,480 --> 01:43:35,750
<i>~</i> Come fly with me,
let's fly, let's fly away <i>~</i>

2300
01:43:35,800 --> 01:43:39,395
<i>~</i> Come fly with me,
let's float down to Peru <i>~</i>

2301
01:43:42,240 --> 01:43:45,198
<i>~</i> In Ilama land
there's a one-man band <i>~</i>

2302
01:43:45,240 --> 01:43:48,198
<i>~</i> And he'll toot his flute
for you <i>~</i>

2303
01:43:48,240 --> 01:43:49,958
<i>(appreciative whistle)</i>

2304
01:43:50,000 --> 01:43:51,069
<i>~</i> Come fly with me<i>... ~</i>

2305
01:43:51,120 --> 01:43:52,189
Hi.

2306
01:43:52,240 --> 01:43:54,708
<i>~... </i>Let's take off
in the blue <i>~</i>

2307
01:43:54,760 --> 01:43:58,070
<i>~</i> Once I get you up there <i>~</i>

2308
01:43:58,120 --> 01:44:00,270
<i>~</i> Where the air is rarefied <i>~</i>

2309
01:44:00,320 --> 01:44:02,470
<i>(wolf whistle)</i>

2310
01:44:02,520 --> 01:44:08,390
<i>~</i> We'll just glide starry-eyed <i>~</i>

2311
01:44:08,440 --> 01:44:11,273
<i>~</i> Once I get you up there<i>... ~</i>

2312
01:44:11,320 --> 01:44:12,719
You see that blonde out front?

2313
01:44:12,760 --> 01:44:13,829
I should have been a pilot.

2314
01:44:13,880 --> 01:44:15,598
Exactly.

2315
01:44:15,640 --> 01:44:16,993
WOMAN <i>(over P.A.)</i>:
Mr. Carl Hanratty

2316
01:44:17,040 --> 01:44:18,393
please pick up
the courtesy telephone.

2317
01:44:18,440 --> 01:44:19,589
Hanratty.

2318
01:44:19,640 --> 01:44:21,676
AMDURSKY:
Carl, your walkie-talkie
wasn't working.

2319
01:44:21,720 --> 01:44:23,073
There's a guy
in a Pan Am uniform

2320
01:44:23,120 --> 01:44:25,680
sitting in a white Coupe DeVille
out in front of Terminal J.

2321
01:44:25,720 --> 01:44:26,789
That's the charter terminal.

2322
01:44:26,840 --> 01:44:28,034
Can you get a look at his face?

2323
01:44:28,080 --> 01:44:29,195
He's got his pilot's cap on.

2324
01:44:29,240 --> 01:44:30,389
Carl, I think it's him!

2325
01:44:30,440 --> 01:44:32,556
<i>~... </i>Just say the words,
and we'll beat the birds <i>~</i>

2326
01:44:32,600 --> 01:44:34,033
<i>~</i> Down to Acapulco Bay<i>... ~</i>

2327
01:44:34,080 --> 01:44:35,354
<i>(siren blaring)</i>

2328
01:44:35,400 --> 01:44:36,799
Watch out, watch out,
watch out!

2329
01:44:36,840 --> 01:44:40,549
<i>~... </i> It's perfect for a flying
honeymoon, they say<i>... ~</i>

2330
01:44:40,600 --> 01:44:42,352
<i>(agents shouting)</i>

2331
01:44:42,400 --> 01:44:43,833
Out of the car, Frank.

2332
01:44:43,880 --> 01:44:45,359
<i>(patrol cars' tires squealing)</i>

2333
01:44:45,400 --> 01:44:46,355
Frank?!

2334
01:44:46,400 --> 01:44:48,391
Step out of the car!

2335
01:44:48,440 --> 01:44:50,635
Keep your hands
where I can see 'em.

2336
01:44:50,680 --> 01:44:52,318
Don't shoot me!
I'm just a driver.

2337
01:44:52,360 --> 01:44:54,351
A man paid me $100
to wear this uniform

2338
01:44:54,400 --> 01:44:55,469
and pick someone up
at the airport.

2339
01:44:55,520 --> 01:44:56,475
Who you picking up?

2340
01:44:57,440 --> 01:44:58,589
Hey!

2341
01:45:02,040 --> 01:45:07,034
<i>~</i> Pack up, let's fly away<i>. ~</i>

2342
01:45:09,720 --> 01:45:12,280
<i>(engine roaring)</i>

2343
01:45:18,640 --> 01:45:21,677
Seven months later

2344
01:45:21,720 --> 01:45:23,233
HANRATTY:
South America, Australia

2345
01:45:23,280 --> 01:45:24,190
Singapore, Egypt.

2346
01:45:24,240 --> 01:45:25,992
The kid's gone
completely out of control.

2347
01:45:26,040 --> 01:45:27,109
Why wasn't I called?

2348
01:45:27,160 --> 01:45:28,559
FOX:
Nobody was called, sir.

2349
01:45:28,600 --> 01:45:31,478
The banks didn't know what
was happening till last week.

2350
01:45:31,520 --> 01:45:32,635
That's impossible.

2351
01:45:32,680 --> 01:45:34,352
They didn't call
'cause it's not counterfeiting.

2352
01:45:34,400 --> 01:45:35,913
- It's something else.
- Well, what is he doing?

2353
01:45:35,960 --> 01:45:37,029
He's making real checks, sir.

2354
01:45:37,080 --> 01:45:37,990
These are so perfect

2355
01:45:38,040 --> 01:45:39,553
the airline didn't know
the difference.

2356
01:45:39,600 --> 01:45:41,272
Last check was cashed
in Madrid a week ago.

2357
01:45:41,320 --> 01:45:42,435
My guess is he's still there.

2358
01:45:42,480 --> 01:45:43,754
We have to leave now, sir.
Today.

2359
01:45:43,800 --> 01:45:45,028
Go where?

2360
01:45:45,080 --> 01:45:46,638
Spain? You want to go to Spain?

2361
01:45:46,680 --> 01:45:47,999
Well, eventually,
he's got to go back

2362
01:45:48,040 --> 01:45:49,189
to where the checks
were printed.

2363
01:45:49,240 --> 01:45:51,117
I think that's why
he's moving back through Europe.

2364
01:45:51,160 --> 01:45:52,752
Look at the map, sir.
He's making a circle.

2365
01:45:52,800 --> 01:45:53,789
He's running out of checks.

2366
01:45:53,840 --> 01:45:55,193
I know it's a...
it's a long shot, sir

2367
01:45:55,240 --> 01:45:57,595
but if we track him from Madrid,
sir, we could still catch him.

2368
01:45:57,640 --> 01:45:59,358
I'm sorry, Carl,
if you couldn't catch him here

2369
01:45:59,400 --> 01:46:00,719
you're not going
to catch him there.

2370
01:46:00,760 --> 01:46:02,557
But, sir, we're going
to let him get away.

2371
01:46:02,600 --> 01:46:06,036
No, Carl, you let him get away.

2372
01:46:15,120 --> 01:46:17,998
<i>(tapping map)</i>

2373
01:46:27,600 --> 01:46:30,478
<i>~ ~</i>

2374
01:46:39,120 --> 01:46:41,998
<i>~ ~</i>

2375
01:46:45,160 --> 01:46:50,598
A perfect one-16th
all the way around.

2376
01:46:50,640 --> 01:46:52,232
Hmm!

2377
01:46:52,280 --> 01:46:54,919
Color separation is flawless.

2378
01:46:57,080 --> 01:46:59,116
There's no bleeding. Hmm.

2379
01:46:59,160 --> 01:47:01,674
Nobody does work like this
in the States.

2380
01:47:01,720 --> 01:47:02,948
Nobody but us.

2381
01:47:03,000 --> 01:47:04,718
HANRATTY:
Where was it printed?

2382
01:47:04,760 --> 01:47:06,910
<i>(chuckling)</i>:
It was printed on a monster...

2383
01:47:06,960 --> 01:47:07,870
A monster.

2384
01:47:07,920 --> 01:47:09,353
...a Heidelberg, an Istra...

2385
01:47:09,400 --> 01:47:10,469
Heidelberg.

2386
01:47:10,520 --> 01:47:12,078
...a dinosaur, four colors.

2387
01:47:12,120 --> 01:47:13,553
You can smell the weight.

2388
01:47:13,600 --> 01:47:15,113
Two tons, without the ink.

2389
01:47:15,160 --> 01:47:16,513
<i>(inhales, clears throat)</i>

2390
01:47:16,560 --> 01:47:18,516
Where do they do printing
like this?

2391
01:47:18,560 --> 01:47:20,118
Germany, Great Britain...

2392
01:47:20,160 --> 01:47:21,070
France.

2393
01:47:21,120 --> 01:47:23,759
BOTH PRINTERS:
France!

2394
01:47:23,800 --> 01:47:25,870
France. Frank's mother said
the name of a village in France

2395
01:47:25,920 --> 01:47:27,035
where they didn't have Sara Lee.

2396
01:47:27,080 --> 01:47:28,559
The village where
she met Frank's father.

2397
01:47:28,600 --> 01:47:29,953
Oh, yeah,
I don't remember, uh...

2398
01:47:30,000 --> 01:47:31,831
It started with an M.
It was, uh, "Mont" something.

2399
01:47:31,880 --> 01:47:32,790
"Mont." Mr. Fox?

2400
01:47:32,840 --> 01:47:33,750
Uh, yes, yes.

2401
01:47:33,800 --> 01:47:35,518
Question: "You met your husband
during the war?"

2402
01:47:35,560 --> 01:47:37,357
Answer: "Yes, I lived
in a small village in France.

2403
01:47:37,400 --> 01:47:38,594
Yeah, right.

2404
01:47:38,640 --> 01:47:40,870
"The kind of place where
they never heard of Sara Lee."

2405
01:47:40,920 --> 01:47:43,150
Tell me you wrote down the name
of the village, Mr. Fox.

2406
01:47:43,200 --> 01:47:46,351
Montrichard.

2407
01:47:46,400 --> 01:47:48,516
CHORUS <i>(in distance)</i>:
<i>~</i> Laeti triumphantes <i>~</i>

2408
01:47:48,560 --> 01:47:50,790
Montrichard, France
Christmas Eve 1967

2409
01:47:50,840 --> 01:47:55,118
<i>~</i> Venite, venite <i>~</i>

2410
01:47:55,160 --> 01:48:00,553
<i>~</i> In Bethlehem <i>~</i>

2411
01:48:00,600 --> 01:48:05,037
<i>~</i> Natum videte <i>~</i>

2412
01:48:05,080 --> 01:48:09,835
<i>~</i> Regem angelorum <i>~</i>

2413
01:48:09,880 --> 01:48:19,596
<i>~</i> Venite adoremus,
Venite adoremus <i>~</i>

2414
01:48:19,640 --> 01:48:21,790
<i>~</i> Venite<i>... ~</i>

2415
01:48:21,840 --> 01:48:24,593
<i>(rhythmic clattering)</i>

2416
01:48:36,120 --> 01:48:37,235
<i>(bell ringing)</i>

2417
01:48:37,280 --> 01:48:38,872
<i>(thumping and fluttering)</i>

2418
01:48:38,920 --> 01:48:40,035
<i>(clattering slows)</i>

2419
01:48:40,080 --> 01:48:40,990
Carl?

2420
01:48:41,040 --> 01:48:42,155
Carl!

2421
01:48:43,560 --> 01:48:44,913
Merry Christmas!

2422
01:48:44,960 --> 01:48:47,679
How is it that we're always
talking on Christmas, Carl?

2423
01:48:47,720 --> 01:48:49,472
Every Christmas
I'm talking to you!

2424
01:48:49,520 --> 01:48:50,635
<i>(laughing)</i>

2425
01:48:50,680 --> 01:48:52,432
Put your shirt on, Frank.
You're under arrest.

2426
01:48:52,480 --> 01:48:54,391
Hey, are you hungry?
Do you want some beans, Carl?

2427
01:48:54,440 --> 01:48:55,793
They got the best
French beans here.

2428
01:48:55,840 --> 01:48:56,750
Here, give these a try.

2429
01:48:56,800 --> 01:48:58,631
There's two dozen French
police officers outside.

2430
01:48:58,680 --> 01:49:00,238
Carl, I gotta tell you,
they're delicious.

2431
01:49:00,280 --> 01:49:01,349
They wanted to bring you in.

2432
01:49:01,400 --> 01:49:02,515
You want a bite?

2433
01:49:02,560 --> 01:49:03,993
But they needed the help
of an American.

2434
01:49:04,040 --> 01:49:05,189
Are you hungry?
You want a bite?

2435
01:49:05,240 --> 01:49:06,798
But I told them
I wouldn't bring them to you

2436
01:49:06,840 --> 01:49:08,432
unless I could put the cuffs
on you myself.

2437
01:49:08,480 --> 01:49:09,993
Well, you have a gun?
You have a gun?

2438
01:49:10,040 --> 01:49:11,109
- No gun?
- No.

2439
01:49:11,160 --> 01:49:12,149
No gun.

2440
01:49:13,760 --> 01:49:15,352
And-and you're...
and you're telling me what?

2441
01:49:15,400 --> 01:49:16,833
There's, uh,
there's uh<i>... (chuckles)</i>

2442
01:49:16,880 --> 01:49:18,677
there's two dozen
French police officers out there

2443
01:49:18,720 --> 01:49:19,709
right now on Christmas Eve?

2444
01:49:19,760 --> 01:49:20,875
That's what you're telling me?

2445
01:49:20,920 --> 01:49:22,114
Yeah.

2446
01:49:22,160 --> 01:49:23,434
<i>(chuckling)</i>:
All right, all right.

2447
01:49:23,480 --> 01:49:25,118
Well, there's no windows here.

2448
01:49:25,160 --> 01:49:27,594
I'm going to take a look
out the front door.

2449
01:49:27,640 --> 01:49:28,709
No! No!

2450
01:49:28,760 --> 01:49:31,354
I told them I'd walk out first
and give a signal.

2451
01:49:31,400 --> 01:49:32,753
Here, you can
put these on yourself.

2452
01:49:32,800 --> 01:49:34,313
No, I can't do that!
I can't do that.

2453
01:49:34,360 --> 01:49:35,429
You know why?

2454
01:49:35,480 --> 01:49:36,515
<i>(panting)</i>

2455
01:49:36,560 --> 01:49:37,993
'Cause I think
you're full of shit.

2456
01:49:38,040 --> 01:49:40,349
I don't... I don't think
there's anyone else out there.

2457
01:49:40,400 --> 01:49:42,231
I think... I think
it's just me and you.

2458
01:49:42,280 --> 01:49:43,474
That's right.

2459
01:49:43,520 --> 01:49:45,397
I think it's just me and you,
and you know what?

2460
01:49:45,440 --> 01:49:47,078
You're going to have
to catch me yourself!

2461
01:49:47,120 --> 01:49:49,680
I wo... we don't have time
for this.

2462
01:49:49,720 --> 01:49:51,790
Ah, that's good. That's good.

2463
01:49:51,840 --> 01:49:54,479
Tell me what you want me to see,
huh?

2464
01:49:54,520 --> 01:49:55,475
I wouldn't lie to you.

2465
01:49:55,520 --> 01:49:56,953
Look, you're wearing
a wedding ring.

2466
01:49:57,000 --> 01:49:58,479
You're wearing
a wedding ring, Carl!

2467
01:49:58,520 --> 01:49:59,555
You lied to me about that!

2468
01:49:59,600 --> 01:50:00,953
Didn't you lie about that?!

2469
01:50:01,000 --> 01:50:02,592
You asked me if I had a family.

2470
01:50:02,640 --> 01:50:04,119
I did, but I don't anymore.

2471
01:50:04,160 --> 01:50:05,991
<i>(phone ringing)</i>

2472
01:50:06,040 --> 01:50:08,315
<i>(anxious breathing)</i>

2473
01:50:10,520 --> 01:50:12,556
<i>(ringing continues)</i>

2474
01:50:12,600 --> 01:50:14,431
Yes? No, no, no,
there is no problem.

2475
01:50:14,480 --> 01:50:15,879
We're coming out right now.

2476
01:50:15,920 --> 01:50:17,797
<i>(laughing)</i>

2477
01:50:17,840 --> 01:50:19,478
Whoa, that was good.
That was good.

2478
01:50:19,520 --> 01:50:21,397
What, did you...
you pay some hotel desk clerk

2479
01:50:21,440 --> 01:50:23,476
to make that call for you,
is that what you did?

2480
01:50:23,520 --> 01:50:24,430
It was Captain Luc.

2481
01:50:24,480 --> 01:50:25,595
I've got one minute
to bring you out.

2482
01:50:25,640 --> 01:50:26,959
Captain Luc? Captain Luc!

2483
01:50:27,000 --> 01:50:27,910
Ooh, Captain Luc.

2484
01:50:27,960 --> 01:50:29,154
Well, Carl, I gotta say

2485
01:50:29,200 --> 01:50:31,191
that-that sounds
pretty official to me

2486
01:50:31,240 --> 01:50:33,310
but like I said, I...
I think it's just

2487
01:50:33,360 --> 01:50:34,634
me and you here,
it's me and you.

2488
01:50:34,680 --> 01:50:36,033
So you're going to have
to catch me.

2489
01:50:36,080 --> 01:50:36,990
Frank. Frank!

2490
01:50:37,040 --> 01:50:38,837
You have to trust me on this!

2491
01:50:38,880 --> 01:50:41,519
These people
have been embarrassed, Frank.

2492
01:50:41,560 --> 01:50:42,629
They're angry.

2493
01:50:42,680 --> 01:50:44,318
You rob their banks,
you steal their money

2494
01:50:44,360 --> 01:50:45,395
you live in their country.

2495
01:50:45,440 --> 01:50:47,158
I told you this was
what was going to happen

2496
01:50:47,200 --> 01:50:48,872
that there was no other way
for it to end.

2497
01:50:48,920 --> 01:50:51,559
Don't make a mistake!

2498
01:50:51,600 --> 01:50:52,715
That's good.

2499
01:50:52,760 --> 01:50:54,955
That's good, Carl, you know?

2500
01:50:55,000 --> 01:50:55,910
Keep pushing that lie.

2501
01:50:55,960 --> 01:50:56,870
Keep pushing it.

2502
01:50:56,920 --> 01:50:58,478
Keep pushing
till you make it true.

2503
01:50:58,520 --> 01:51:00,909
They're going to kill you!

2504
01:51:00,960 --> 01:51:03,520
You walk out that door,
they're going to kill you.

2505
01:51:03,560 --> 01:51:05,471
<i>(panting)</i>

2506
01:51:08,280 --> 01:51:10,396
Is that the truth?

2507
01:51:13,880 --> 01:51:16,110
Yeah.

2508
01:51:19,800 --> 01:51:22,268
You have any children, Carl?

2509
01:51:22,320 --> 01:51:25,869
I have a four-year-old daughter.

2510
01:51:25,920 --> 01:51:28,434
You swear on your daughter?

2511
01:51:30,360 --> 01:51:32,715
You swear?

2512
01:51:36,720 --> 01:51:39,917
You swear?

2513
01:51:39,960 --> 01:51:42,030
<i>(handcuffs clacking)</i>

2514
01:51:49,760 --> 01:51:54,151
CHORUS:
<i>~</i> Redit ce chant melodieux <i>~</i>

2515
01:51:54,200 --> 01:52:01,834
<i>~</i> Gloria <i>~</i>

2516
01:52:01,880 --> 01:52:05,316
<i>~</i> In excelsius Deo <i>~</i>

2517
01:52:05,360 --> 01:52:08,352
<i>~</i> Gloria<i>... ~</i>

2518
01:52:08,400 --> 01:52:10,470
That was really good, Carl.

2519
01:52:10,520 --> 01:52:13,273
<i>(car approaching)</i>

2520
01:52:13,320 --> 01:52:15,151
<i>(sirens blaring)</i>

2521
01:52:15,200 --> 01:52:17,191
<i>(chorus continues singing)</i>

2522
01:52:17,240 --> 01:52:18,468
<i>(tires screeching)</i>

2523
01:52:18,520 --> 01:52:19,714
<i>(officer shouting in French)</i>

2524
01:52:19,760 --> 01:52:20,670
I have him in custody.

2525
01:52:20,720 --> 01:52:21,869
I got him.

2526
01:52:21,920 --> 01:52:23,512
I got him! It's all right!

2527
01:52:23,560 --> 01:52:24,879
<i>(shouting continues)</i>

2528
01:52:24,920 --> 01:52:25,989
It's all right!

2529
01:52:26,040 --> 01:52:27,678
I got him!

2530
01:52:27,720 --> 01:52:28,709
<i>(speaking in French)</i>

2531
01:52:28,760 --> 01:52:30,432
<i>(officer shouting excitedly)</i>

2532
01:52:30,480 --> 01:52:32,835
Hey, I want it...
I want it on the record.

2533
01:52:32,880 --> 01:52:35,440
Frank Abagnale surrendered
of his own accord.

2534
01:52:35,480 --> 01:52:37,710
Understood? Understood?

2535
01:52:37,760 --> 01:52:38,670
Where are you taking him?

2536
01:52:38,720 --> 01:52:39,630
<i>(speaking in French)</i>

2537
01:52:39,680 --> 01:52:40,590
I'm... I'm supposed to go.

2538
01:52:40,640 --> 01:52:42,312
Where are you taking him?

2539
01:52:42,360 --> 01:52:43,554
Let me in the...

2540
01:52:43,600 --> 01:52:44,510
Let me in the car!

2541
01:52:44,560 --> 01:52:45,549
<i>(shouting continues)</i>

2542
01:52:45,600 --> 01:52:47,716
Hey! Let me in the car!

2543
01:52:47,760 --> 01:52:48,875
<i>~</i> Gloria<i>... ~</i>

2544
01:52:48,920 --> 01:52:49,989
<i>(engine starts)</i>

2545
01:52:50,040 --> 01:52:51,155
Don't worry, Frank!

2546
01:52:51,200 --> 01:52:53,156
I'll have you extradited
back to the United States.

2547
01:52:53,200 --> 01:52:54,189
Don't worry.

2548
01:52:54,240 --> 01:52:56,754
<i>(siren wailing)</i>

2549
01:52:58,880 --> 01:53:07,117
<i>~</i> Gloria <i>~</i>

2550
01:53:09,280 --> 01:53:13,831
<i>~</i> In excelsius Deo<i>. ~</i>

2551
01:53:13,880 --> 01:53:16,633
Carl...

2552
01:53:16,680 --> 01:53:19,069
Carl, you have to remember

2553
01:53:19,120 --> 01:53:22,635
to let me call my father
when we land.

2554
01:53:22,680 --> 01:53:24,511
I just want to,
I want to talk to him

2555
01:53:24,560 --> 01:53:27,472
before he sees me on television
or something like that.

2556
01:53:36,920 --> 01:53:38,433
Carl, look.

2557
01:53:38,480 --> 01:53:40,436
That's LaGuardia right there.

2558
01:53:40,480 --> 01:53:42,118
Runway 4-4.

2559
01:53:42,160 --> 01:53:44,720
Frank, your father is dead.

2560
01:53:44,760 --> 01:53:46,637
I'm sorry.

2561
01:53:46,680 --> 01:53:50,116
I didn't want to say anything
till we got closer to home.

2562
01:53:50,160 --> 01:53:54,676
He-He... He fell down some steps
at Grand Central Station

2563
01:53:54,720 --> 01:53:56,676
trying to catch a train.

2564
01:53:56,720 --> 01:53:58,950
I didn't want to be the one
to tell you.

2565
01:53:59,000 --> 01:54:02,117
You're lying, right?

2566
01:54:02,160 --> 01:54:04,355
You said I could talk to him.

2567
01:54:04,400 --> 01:54:05,310
Carl, who are you to...

2568
01:54:05,360 --> 01:54:07,112
who are you to say
something like that, huh?

2569
01:54:07,160 --> 01:54:08,718
Who are you
to say something like that?

2570
01:54:08,760 --> 01:54:09,954
You said I could talk to him.

2571
01:54:10,000 --> 01:54:11,877
He fell, and he...
and he broke his neck.

2572
01:54:11,920 --> 01:54:14,309
I'm sorry.

2573
01:54:14,360 --> 01:54:16,874
I'm really sorry.

2574
01:54:23,640 --> 01:54:26,518
<i>(panting)</i>

2575
01:54:26,560 --> 01:54:27,834
<i>(hits seat)</i>

2576
01:54:27,880 --> 01:54:29,438
<i>(sobbing)</i>:
Goddamn it!

2577
01:54:29,480 --> 01:54:31,436
Carl, I'm going to be sick!

2578
01:54:31,480 --> 01:54:32,879
<i>-(people muttering)</i>
- It's all right.

2579
01:54:32,920 --> 01:54:33,875
It's all right. It's okay.

2580
01:54:33,920 --> 01:54:35,239
Carl, I got to go
to the bathroom.

2581
01:54:35,280 --> 01:54:36,190
I'm going to be sick.

2582
01:54:36,240 --> 01:54:37,958
Sure.
Let's go in the bathroom.

2583
01:54:39,320 --> 01:54:41,231
<i>(panting)</i>

2584
01:54:44,720 --> 01:54:45,994
Goddamn it!

2585
01:54:46,040 --> 01:54:49,828
<i>(sobbing)</i>

2586
01:54:49,880 --> 01:54:51,359
<i>(pounding)</i>

2587
01:54:51,400 --> 01:54:52,753
<i>(murmuring)</i>

2588
01:54:52,800 --> 01:54:55,234
<i>(panting)</i>

2589
01:54:55,280 --> 01:54:57,271
<i>(panting slows)</i>

2590
01:54:58,600 --> 01:55:00,431
<i>(Frank panting)</i>

2591
01:55:02,880 --> 01:55:05,758
<i>(whispering)</i>:
Oh, Daddy...

2592
01:55:08,280 --> 01:55:09,679
You'll have take your seat, sir.

2593
01:55:09,720 --> 01:55:11,233
I've told you twice.
We're landing.

2594
01:55:11,280 --> 01:55:12,633
- Sorry. Thank you...
- All of you.

2595
01:55:12,680 --> 01:55:13,829
Frank! Come on now.

2596
01:55:13,880 --> 01:55:15,359
- Frank?
- We're landing in six minutes.

2597
01:55:15,400 --> 01:55:16,879
All of you need to be
in your seats

2598
01:55:16,920 --> 01:55:19,115
- With your seat belts fastened.
- Frank, open the door!

2599
01:55:19,160 --> 01:55:20,718
Frank!

2600
01:55:22,520 --> 01:55:24,078
- You do it.
- Yeah.

2601
01:55:35,760 --> 01:55:38,228
<i>(engines decelerating)</i>

2602
01:55:44,520 --> 01:55:46,829
<i>(grunting)</i>

2603
01:55:49,560 --> 01:55:50,788
<i>(frustrated sigh)</i>

2604
01:55:50,840 --> 01:55:52,159
<i>(grunting)</i>

2605
01:55:52,200 --> 01:55:54,077
Frank! Frank!

2606
01:55:54,120 --> 01:55:56,076
<i>(engines roaring)</i>

2607
01:55:56,120 --> 01:55:58,190
<i>(tires squealing)</i>

2608
01:55:58,240 --> 01:56:00,754
HANRATTY:
All right, remain seated,
everyone, please.

2609
01:56:00,800 --> 01:56:02,518
FBI. Stay seated.
FBI. Stay seated.

2610
01:56:02,560 --> 01:56:05,472
<i>(engines whining)</i>

2611
01:56:10,600 --> 01:56:11,953
- Please remain seated!
- Stay seated.

2612
01:56:12,000 --> 01:56:13,194
STEWARDESS:
You must stay seated

2613
01:56:13,240 --> 01:56:15,674
until the aircraft
has come to a complete stop.

2614
01:56:15,720 --> 01:56:17,199
HANRATTY:
God almighty.

2615
01:56:17,240 --> 01:56:20,835
NAT KING COLE:
<i>~</i> Chestnuts roasting
on an open fire<i>... ~</i>

2616
01:56:20,880 --> 01:56:23,713
<i>(panting)</i>

2617
01:56:23,760 --> 01:56:30,677
<i>~</i> Jack Frost nipping
at your nose <i>~</i>

2618
01:56:30,720 --> 01:56:35,840
<i>~</i> Yuletide carols
being sung by a choir <i>~</i>

2619
01:56:35,880 --> 01:56:41,318
<i>~</i> And folks dressed up
like Eskimos <i>~</i>

2620
01:56:41,360 --> 01:56:44,193
<i>~</i> Everybody knows <i>~</i>

2621
01:56:44,240 --> 01:56:49,234
<i>~</i> A turkey and some mistletoe <i>~</i>

2622
01:56:49,280 --> 01:56:53,751
<i>~</i> Help to make
the season bright <i>~</i>

2623
01:56:53,800 --> 01:56:55,950
<i>(quietly blowing notes)</i>

2624
01:56:56,000 --> 01:57:00,278
<i>~</i> Tiny tots with their eyes
all aglow <i>~</i>

2625
01:57:00,320 --> 01:57:04,154
<i>~</i> Will find it hard
to sleep tonight<i>... ~</i>

2626
01:57:04,200 --> 01:57:06,077
What's your name?

2627
01:57:06,120 --> 01:57:07,109
<i>(blows note)</i>

2628
01:57:07,160 --> 01:57:09,116
<i>~</i> They know that Santa's
on his way<i>... ~</i>

2629
01:57:09,160 --> 01:57:12,516
Where's your mommy?

2630
01:57:12,560 --> 01:57:16,951
<i>~... </i>He's loaded lots of toys
and goodies on his sleigh <i>~</i>

2631
01:57:17,000 --> 01:57:19,753
<i>(blows note)</i>

2632
01:57:19,800 --> 01:57:24,999
<i>~</i> And every mother's child
is gonna spy <i>~</i>

2633
01:57:25,040 --> 01:57:27,429
<i>~</i> To see if reindeer
really know how to fly<i>... ~</i>

2634
01:57:27,480 --> 01:57:30,438
<i>(brakes squeaking)</i>

2635
01:57:30,480 --> 01:57:35,429
<i>~</i> And so I'm offering
this simple phrase<i>... ~</i>

2636
01:57:35,480 --> 01:57:38,438
<i>(men shouting indistinctly)</i>

2637
01:57:38,480 --> 01:57:44,589
<i>~</i> To kids from one to 92 <i>~</i>

2638
01:57:44,640 --> 01:57:47,950
<i>~</i> Although it's been said
many times <i>~</i>

2639
01:57:48,000 --> 01:57:51,276
<i>~</i> Many ways:
"Merry Christmas..." <i>~</i>

2640
01:57:51,320 --> 01:57:52,958
Hands behind your head!

2641
01:57:53,000 --> 01:57:54,877
<i>~... </i>To you<i>. ~</i>

2642
01:57:54,920 --> 01:57:56,273
Carl, get me in the car,
please.

2643
01:57:56,320 --> 01:57:59,357
Get me in the car.

2644
01:57:59,400 --> 01:58:01,277
HANRATTY:
Put him in.

2645
01:58:01,320 --> 01:58:04,153
<i>(piano playing interlude</i>
<i>in "The Christmas Song")</i>

2646
01:58:04,200 --> 01:58:06,111
<i>(handcuffs latching)</i>

2647
01:58:15,200 --> 01:58:16,599
<i>~ ~</i>

2648
01:58:16,640 --> 01:58:20,076
JUDGE:
<i>Taking into account</i>
<i>the gravity of these crimes</i>

2649
01:58:20,120 --> 01:58:23,795
<i>your history of bold</i>
<i>and elusive behavior</i>

2650
01:58:23,840 --> 01:58:26,115
<i>and your complete lack</i>
<i>of respect</i>

2651
01:58:26,160 --> 01:58:28,469
<i>for the laws</i>
<i>of the United States</i>

2652
01:58:28,520 --> 01:58:31,512
<i>I have no choice</i>
<i>but to ignore your request</i>

2653
01:58:31,560 --> 01:58:33,391
<i>to be treated as a minor</i>

2654
01:58:33,440 --> 01:58:35,192
<i>and sentence you to 12 years</i>

2655
01:58:35,240 --> 01:58:38,312
<i>in Atlanta's</i>
<i>maximum security prison</i>

2656
01:58:38,360 --> 01:58:41,557
<i>and recommend strongly</i>
<i>that you be kept in isolation</i>

2657
01:58:41,600 --> 01:58:43,591
<i>for the entirety</i>
<i>of that sentence. </i>

2658
01:58:43,640 --> 01:58:46,950
<i>~... </i>"Merry Christmas to you." <i>~</i>

2659
01:58:47,000 --> 01:58:50,436
<i>(song ends with guitar playing</i>
<i>"Jingle Bells" riff)</i>

2660
01:58:55,640 --> 01:58:57,358
Use that door over there.

2661
01:58:57,400 --> 01:58:59,755
<i>(phone ringing)</i>

2662
01:58:59,800 --> 01:59:02,758
<i>(indistinct voices)</i>

2663
01:59:02,800 --> 01:59:04,677
PRISONER:
...and give everyone my love.

2664
01:59:04,720 --> 01:59:06,312
I think about them all the time.

2665
01:59:16,520 --> 01:59:18,590
<i>(indistinct conversations</i>
<i>in distance)</i>

2666
01:59:22,840 --> 01:59:24,068
<i>(sighs deeply)</i>

2667
01:59:24,120 --> 01:59:26,395
Merry Christmas, Frank.

2668
01:59:28,680 --> 01:59:31,194
Hey, I got you
some comic books here.

2669
01:59:37,640 --> 01:59:38,834
How's your daughter?

2670
01:59:38,880 --> 01:59:40,074
What was her name?

2671
01:59:40,120 --> 01:59:41,030
Grace.

2672
01:59:41,080 --> 01:59:42,308
Well... I don't know.

2673
01:59:42,360 --> 01:59:44,430
She lives with her mother
in Chicago

2674
01:59:44,480 --> 01:59:46,357
and I don't get to see her much.

2675
01:59:47,800 --> 01:59:49,313
What's in the briefcase?

2676
01:59:49,360 --> 01:59:51,237
Oh. I'm on my way
to the airport.

2677
01:59:51,280 --> 01:59:53,157
It's a paperhanger

2678
01:59:53,200 --> 01:59:55,316
who's working his way
through Minnesota.

2679
01:59:55,360 --> 01:59:56,679
<i>(chuckling)</i>

2680
01:59:56,720 --> 02:00:00,076
Aw, geez, he's...
he's driving us crazy.

2681
02:00:00,120 --> 02:00:01,633
You got any of the checks?

2682
02:00:01,680 --> 02:00:04,069
Yeah, yeah, I got a...
a counterfeit that he drew

2683
02:00:04,120 --> 02:00:05,838
on the Great Lakes
Savings and Loan.

2684
02:00:05,880 --> 02:00:07,711
See, he's just using
a stencil machine

2685
02:00:07,760 --> 02:00:09,193
and an Underwood.

2686
02:00:09,240 --> 02:00:11,754
Yeah, it's a teller at the bank.

2687
02:00:11,800 --> 02:00:13,074
Say again?

2688
02:00:13,120 --> 02:00:14,633
l-It's definitely a teller,
Carl.

2689
02:00:14,680 --> 02:00:16,671
I mean, banks,
they always use hand-stamps

2690
02:00:16,720 --> 02:00:18,119
for the dates, see.

2691
02:00:18,160 --> 02:00:19,798
They get used
over and over again

2692
02:00:19,840 --> 02:00:21,159
so they always get worn out

2693
02:00:21,200 --> 02:00:22,997
and the numbers
are always cracking.

2694
02:00:23,040 --> 02:00:26,635
The sixes and the nines...
see, they go first.

2695
02:00:28,560 --> 02:00:30,357
Thanks.

2696
02:00:30,400 --> 02:00:32,311
<i>(buzzer sounding)</i>

2697
02:00:34,800 --> 02:00:36,358
MAN:
<i>I'd like you to take a look</i>

2698
02:00:36,400 --> 02:00:37,674
<i>at something for me. </i>

2699
02:00:42,320 --> 02:00:44,436
Tell me what you think.

2700
02:00:44,480 --> 02:00:46,869
<i>(clears throat)</i>

2701
02:00:46,920 --> 02:00:48,433
That's a fake.

2702
02:00:48,480 --> 02:00:49,913
How do you know?

2703
02:00:49,960 --> 02:00:51,075
You haven't looked at it.

2704
02:00:51,120 --> 02:00:53,509
Well, there's
no perforated edge, right?

2705
02:00:53,560 --> 02:00:56,438
I mean, this... this check
was hand-cut, not fed.

2706
02:00:56,480 --> 02:00:58,596
Yeah...

2707
02:00:58,640 --> 02:00:59,834
Paper is double-bonded

2708
02:00:59,880 --> 02:01:02,110
much too heavy
to be a bank check.

2709
02:01:02,160 --> 02:01:05,948
Magnetic ink, it's, uh,
raised against my fingers

2710
02:01:06,000 --> 02:01:07,228
instead of flat.

2711
02:01:07,280 --> 02:01:08,349
<i>(sniffing)</i>

2712
02:01:08,400 --> 02:01:09,799
